1zh.title: Bayes's Rule (log odds form)
1zh.clickbait: By representing beliefs using log odds, we can arithmetically sum the strength of evidence and the degree of prior belief.
1zh.text:
# Definition

Bayes's Rule states that the prior odds times the likelihood ratio equals the posterior odds.  We can instead just take the logarithms of these quantities and add them.

Letting $H_i$ and $H_j$ denote hypotheses and $e$ denote evidence:

$\log \big ( \dfrac
   {\mathbb P(H_i)}
   {\mathbb P(H_j)}
\big )
+
\log \big ( \dfrac
   {\mathbb P(e|H_i)}
   {\mathbb P(e|H_j)}
\big ) 
=
\log \big ( \dfrac
   {\mathbb P(H_i|e)}
   {\mathbb P(H_j|e)}
\big )
$


This *log odds* representation has a number of convenient properties, discussed below.

# Meaning

We can visualize the likelihoods of the evidence, given hypotheses, as competing forces that "pull" our belief towards those hypotheses.  The log odds representation makes this visualization exact.

Again the Diseasitis example:

> 20% of the patients in the screening population start out with Diseasitis. Among patients with Diseasitis, 90% turn the tongue depressor black. 30% of the patients without Diseasitis will also turn the tongue depressor black. Among all the patients with black tongue depressors, how many have Diseasitis?

We can visualize starting with 20% [1rm prior] belief on a belief-bar ranging from 0% probability of being sick to 100% probability of being sick:

![prior belief bar](https://i.imgur.com/k0ijGqK.png?0)

The test results then produce pulls of 30% likelihood coming from the "healthy" direction, and 90% likelihood coming from the "sick" direction:

![likelihood pulls](https://i.imgur.com/bl3gSoC.png?0)

The imbalance of these two pulls then shifts the belief toward the stronger magnet-likelihood:

![belief pulled](https://i.imgur.com/FelNlce.png?0)

The problem with this image is that it's qualitatively but not quantitatively useful.  The excess of 90% over 30% doesn't correspond in any *immediately* visible way to the pull from 20% to 43%.  If the two magnets had been pulling with strengths of, say, 0.1% from healthy vs. 0.8% from sick, then the physical metaphor would suggest a weaker movement of the belief bar, but the actual change would have been much greater, pulling the bar to 67% probability.

Is there a version of this metaphor that is quantitatively exact?

Indeed there is.  Suppose the prior odds for a hypothesis $H$ are 1 : 16.  We take the logarithm of the corresponding unidimensional representation 1/16, in base 2 for convenience, and obtain this log odds representation of the prior belief:

$\log_2 (\dfrac{\mathbb P(H)}{\mathbb P(\neg H)}) = -4 \text{ bits}$

Here "bits" denotes that we have taken the log base 2 of something; log odds of -4 bits tells us that the odds are 1 : 16 against something.

Suppose we now see evidence $e$ with a likelihood ratio of 8 : 1 favoring $H$ over $\neg H.$  We will call this +3 bits of evidence.

$\log_2 (\dfrac{\mathbb P(e|H)}{\mathbb P(e|\neg H)}) = +3 \text{ bits}$

Our posterior belief will be -4 bits + +3 bits = -1 bit, corresponding to posterior odds of 1 : 2 against the hypothesis.

So if you want to represent likelihoods as pulling magnets, they pull on the log odds, and they pull with strength corresponding to the log-likelihood of the evidence given that hypothesis.

This also suggests that we should think of *strength of belief* in terms of log odds, since it's "strength of belief" in this sense that tells us the quantity of evidence required to change the mind of a rational agent.

(Actually, since log-likelihoods are never positive - no likelihood greater than $1$ whose log is 0 - our belief is really being attracted to the hypothesis that has the negative logarithm closest to 0.  We should really visualize hypotheses radiating repulsive pushes corresponding to how much they make the evidence surprising, with the net force on our belief moving it toward the hypotheses that radiate the least surprise.  But we can also still imagine high likelihoods as pulling more and low likelihoods as pulling less, so long as the absolute distance between pulls still corresponds to the log of the likelihood ratio between them.)

## Example 1

To use a real-life example, a study of Chinese blood donors found that roughly 1 in 100,000 of them had HIV (as determined by a very reliable gold-standard test).  The non-gold-standard test used for initial screening had a *sensitivity* of 99.7% and a *specificity* of 99.8%, meaning respectively that $\mathbb P(positive|HIV) = .997$ and that $\mathbb P(\neg positive|\neg HIV) = .998 \implies \mathbb P(positive | \neg HIV) = .002.$

This establishes a likelihood ratio of 500 : 1 favoring HIV over non-HIV for a positive screening result.  The prior odds were 1 : 100,000 against HIV.  So using Fermi calculations to within an order of magnitude, we have prior belief of roughly -5 orders of magnitude, evidence of less than +3 orders of magnitude (actually 2.7 orders of magnitude), and posterior belief should be less than -2 orders of magnitude, i.e., more improbable than 1 : 100 against HIV.  Someone with a positive result on the screening test for HIV *really really* should not panic!

Using this log odds representation, the same strength of evidence will always shift belief by the same additive amount - we move upward by the same 2.7 orders of magnitude in belief, whether we started from -5 orders of magnitude or -3 orders of magnitude.

## Example 2

> Two barrels each contain plastic eggs painted various colors.  In both barrels, 11% of the eggs contain valuable pearls and 89% are empty.  In the first barrel, 4% of the pearl-containing eggs are painted blue, and 8% of the non-pearl-containing eggs are painted blue.  In the second barrel, 13% of the pearl-containing eggs are painted blue, and 26% of the non-pearl-containing eggs are painted blue.  Would you rather have a blue egg from the first or second barrel?

The [1rq likelihood ratio] summarizes everything there is to know about the *strength of evidence*.  The relative ratio between likelihoods determines how strongly the evidence pulls on net, in which direction.

The first barrel's likelihood ratio 4% to 8% for pearl vs. non-pearl eggs being painted blue, and for the second barrel it's 13% vs. 26%.  Either way, observing "blue" is the same strength of evidence against the egg containing a pearl (-1 bits).  And the prior belief in the pearl is also the same between barrels.  So it doesn't matter which barrel you pick from, and this is visible at a glance.

(But if you want to know the exact posterior odds of obtaining a pearl:   11% : 89% = odds of 1 : 8 = -3 bits of belief in the pearl.  We saw -1 bits of evidence.  The result is -4 bits of belief  6% probability.)

# Exposing infinite credences

The log-odds representation also exposes the degree to which $0$ and $1$ are very unusual among the classical probabilities.  For example, if we assign probability $0$ or $1$ to a hypothesis, no amount of evidence can change our mind about it, ever.

In the log odds form, credences range from $-\infty$ to $+\infty,$ with the infinite extremes corresponding to probability $0$ and $1$ which can thereby be seen as "infinite credences".  This may help motivate the justification for [Cromwell's Rule](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cromwell%27s_rule).

While we do have mathematical need for the notions of $0$ and $1$ probability, e.g. in expressing the sum of $\mathbb P(X) + \mathbb P(\neg X),$ in some ways these infinite credences $0$ and $1$ behave like 'special objects' or 'special cases' rather than part of the ordinary spectrum of the probabilities.  Statements like "After seeing a piece of strong evidence, my belief should never be exactly what it was previously" become false, just as statements like "subtracting 1 from a number produces a lower number" become false if you insist on regarding positive infinity as a number.

# Exposing extreme credences

On a more mundane level, the log-odds representation exposes the idea that a probability of 0.0001 is significantly more extreme than a probability of 0.01, even though a probability of 0.1001 is not much more lower than 0.11.  A graph of log odds doesn't cut off and compress the vast distances available near the "extremes" of the probability spectrum going from $0$ to $1$, and exhibits the "belief bar" as carrying on indefinitely in both directions.
